    <message>
      <heading>Wed May 29 (Jasurin)    :: &amp;gQuest Theory&amp;n</heading>
      <slot>7</slot>
      <level>203</level>
      <author>0</author>
      <date>0</date>
      <text>I'd like to take this opportunity to respond to Etaine and Madison and the
comments they have made about ways in which they would like to see quests
run, and the dynamics they would like to develop.  I think I have a pretty
solid basis upon which to make observation, having been in and run as many
roleplay quests as probably anyone else around here.

Small Group Quests - Need to have a strong theme and a group of people who
are previously invested in the story - i.e., people with an agenda.  This
is generally satisfied when people come to an Imm with a quest idea, but
rarely happens when an Imm simply gechos for quest participants.  If you
try to run a small group quest without that sort of situation, a couple of
relatively serious problems tend to crop up:
&amp;go&amp;n The plotline is immediately limited, since its hard to come up with
an exciting activity for two unrelated characters on the fly.
&amp;go&amp;n The Imm gets bored out of his/her mind by tedious tavern roleplay.
&amp;go&amp;n The Imm tends to feel like his/her time is being wasted on roleplay
which could quite easily occur without his/her assistance.
&amp;go&amp;n The people get bored with roleplay they could do any time on their
own, and are less likely to join future quests, perpetuating the problem.
The implications of these points for off-time roleplay are obvious.  Now,
I have in the past seen attempts made, and made a few myself, to arrange
off-time roleplay.  They tend to end in dismal failure, for the above
reasons.

Prescheduled and Ongoing Quests - Are virtually impossible to perpetuate.
I have done things of this sort many times, and there are 2-3 ways in which
those efforts invariably end:
&amp;go&amp;n People simply can't consistantly make it, and the participants at
later sessions don't get the plot.  Not enough people are involved to keep
the story meaningful, and it ends up being a wasted effort at continuity.
&amp;go&amp;n People simply don't care enough to commit their characters to any
sort of long-term activity in the first place.  I tried to get a group of
characters together for an IC &quot;Quest&quot; (over a period of time) during the
last summer.  I had a grand total of 1 positive response over the 3 weeks
the offer was on the board.  I was forced to drop it.

Now, here's the good news.  Most of these problems can be overcome by a
single very simple expedient.  Rather than expecting Imms to run around
in circles and try to anticipate the needs, desires, and enthusiasms of
the playerbase, morts can get together and come up with things they would
like to see, and bring a proposal to an Imm (especially me).  If you can
get an idea and a group together, I am more than happy to run it, because
I can focus on building a story around whatever framework you give me and
spend less time feeling like I am trying to herd cats into a room to go
IC and roleplay.

-&amp;gJasurin&amp;n
</text>
    </message>
